AI Chinese Learning Coach — Implementation Plan
Below is a practical, opinionated plan. I've tried to make every recommendation concrete enough to act on, and I've woven your constraints (tutor-voice, OCR-uncertainty isolation, evidence-based weakness detection) into the design itself rather than listing them as afterthoughts.

1. System Architecture
A modular monolith is the right starting point — not microservices. You get clean separation of concerns without the operational overhead, and you can peel services off later if needed.
High-level components:

Web client (Next.js) — student-facing, mobile-responsive from day one
API layer (FastAPI) — REST + a few streaming endpoints for live AI feedback
Async worker pool (Celery/ARQ) — handles OCR calls, LLM calls, and weakness recomputation
Postgres — all structured data
Redis — cache + job queue broker
Object storage (S3 / R2 / Aliyun OSS) — uploaded images, with signed URLs
External AI services — LLM provider(s) + OCR provider
Observability — Sentry for errors, PostHog for product analytics, simple logging to start

The critical architectural decision: submissions flow through a pipeline, not a single request. Upload → preprocess → OCR (if image) → verification → analysis → error extraction → weakness update. Each stage writes state to the DB so you can retry, inspect, and audit. Students see progress as it happens rather than staring at a spinner.

2. Database Design
Postgres. Here are the core tables with the fields that matter; I've omitted obvious ones like timestamps and soft-delete flags.
users — id, email, display_name, grade_level, school (nullable), locale, created_at
submissions — id, user_id, type (writing | reading | revision), source (typed | photo | scan), image_url (nullable), raw_ocr_text, verified_text, ocr_confidence_overall, ocr_char_confidences (jsonb), status (uploaded/ocr_done/verified/analyzed/failed), task_id (optional link to a writing prompt)
analyses — id, submission_id, rubric_id, scores (jsonb: e.g. {content: 18/25, structure: 15/20, ...}), overall_score, model_name, model_version, prompt_version, coach_feedback_text, created_at
errors — id, submission_id, analysis_id, category, subcategory, evidence_span (text), char_offset_start, char_offset_end, suggestion, severity (1–3), ocr_suspect (boolean), confidence (0–1)
The ocr_suspect flag is the single most important column for your "OCR uncertainty ≠ weakness" constraint. Any error whose evidence span overlaps low-confidence OCR characters is flagged, and the weakness aggregator excludes these rows entirely.
weakness_profiles — id, user_id, category, subcategory, evidence_count, evidence_submission_ids (array), severity_ewma (exponentially weighted moving average), first_seen_at, last_seen_at, status (watching | confirmed | improving | resolved)
revision_sessions — id, user_id, original_submission_id, revised_text, targeted_error_ids (array), improvement_delta (jsonb)
rubrics — id, grade_level, type, rubric_json (criteria + weights + descriptors per score band)
writing_tasks — id, grade_level, genre, prompt_text, guidance (teacher-authored), suggested_length
feedback_events — id, user_id, target_type (error | suggestion), target_id, reaction (helpful | wrong | confusing), note — this is gold for improving prompts and calibrating the model over time.

3. Frontend Pages
The UX should feel like a patient tutor, not a grading machine. Every page should communicate progress and agency.
The student lands on a Dashboard that shows a one-sentence coach greeting, current focus areas (at most 2–3, never a wall of weaknesses), a streak or consistency indicator, and recent submissions. No shame metrics.
New Submission offers three paths: paste/type, upload photo, or continue from a prompt. If a prompt is chosen, the rubric is shown upfront so the student writes toward it.
OCR Verification is a dedicated step for photo submissions. The original image sits alongside the extracted text, low-confidence characters are highlighted, and the student can tap-to-correct. This page is where you earn trust. Make it fast and kind.
Submission Detail is an annotated view — the essay with inline error chips, grouped by category in a sidebar, each expandable to show the coach's suggestion in tutor-voice. Strengths are shown too, not just errors. A "Start Revision" button leads to…
Revision Workspace — side-by-side original and editable revision, with the targeted errors checklist. The AI offers Socratic hints ("This paragraph's topic sentence — what's the one thing you want the reader to believe?") rather than rewrites. When the student submits the revision, it's analyzed again and the delta is shown.
Weakness Report is a longitudinal view — categories with trend lines, example evidence, and "what to practice next" recommendations. Crucially, weaknesses that are improving are celebrated explicitly.
Reading Practice (Phase 3) presents a passage, comprehension questions, and after submission, analysis of the student's answers against a rubric.
Profile / Settings — grade level, data controls, notifications.

4. Backend Services
Even as a modular monolith, organize code around these domains:

Auth — JWT, email/password to start, SSO later
Submission — upload intake, status tracking, image handling
OCR orchestration — calls external OCR, post-processes confidences, writes to submissions
Analysis orchestration — loads rubric, builds prompt, calls LLM, parses structured output, writes analyses + errors
Weakness aggregation — triggered after each analysis; updates weakness_profiles; separately runnable as a batch job for backfills
Revision — creates revision session, re-analyzes, computes deltas
Content — rubrics, writing tasks, reading passages (admin-curated)
Feedback capture — student reactions to AI output

One architectural rule worth stating: the weakness aggregator must be idempotent and independent of the analysis step. You'll want to re-run it when you change taxonomy or rules, without re-calling the LLM.

5. OCR and AI Workflow
This is where your product philosophy either shines or breaks down. The workflow below is designed around your constraint that OCR uncertainty must never become student weakness.
Image path:

Client-side: compress, rotate, basic auto-crop hint
Server: deskew, denoise, contrast normalize (OpenCV)
Call OCR provider (Baidu OCR has the best Chinese handwriting accuracy in my experience; Tencent is a close second; Google Vision is weaker on handwritten 简体 but fine on printed). Request per-character confidence if supported.
Build a confidence map: characters below ~0.75 are "suspect," runs of 3+ suspect chars are "high-suspect regions"
Show verification UI — student confirms or corrects
The verified_text is what goes to analysis; the original OCR text is kept for audit

Analysis path (writing):

Load the rubric for the student's grade level and the task genre
Build a structured prompt that asks the LLM for (a) rubric scores with justification, (b) a list of errors in a strict JSON schema, (c) a coach-voice overall feedback paragraph, (d) 2–3 revision priorities
Call the LLM with JSON-mode / tool-use for reliable parsing
For each error, compute whether its span overlaps OCR-suspect regions. If yes → set ocr_suspect = true. These errors are shown to the student framed as "Double-check this — we weren't sure we read it right" rather than "You made an error."
Write results; trigger weakness aggregation

Prompt design principles that matter specifically for this product:

Give the model the rubric descriptors verbatim so its scores are anchored
Require evidence spans (character offsets or exact quotes) for every error — no vague "your structure is weak"
Explicitly instruct tutor-voice: encouraging, specific, ask-before-telling
Forbid full rewrites in feedback (this is the anti-cheating guardrail at the prompt level)

For the coaching/revision layer, a smaller, faster model is fine. Reserve your strongest model for the initial analysis.

6. Weakness Detection Logic
Start with a taxonomy you can defend to a Chinese teacher. A reasonable starting set:

1. 字詞
錯別字 — 錯寫、漏寫或多寫筆畫。

形近字 — 字形相近而混淆。

同音字 — 讀音相同但意義不同。

詞語搭配不當 — 動賓或修飾語組合不自然。

2. 語法
語序 — 句子成分排列順序錯誤。

成分殘缺 — 缺少主語、謂語或賓語等核心成分。

搭配不當 — 詞與詞之間的邏輯關係不成立。

句式雜糅 — 兩種句式混雜使用，導致結構混亂。

3. 標點
逗號誤用 — 停頓位置不當。

句號/問號混淆 — 陳述句與疑問句語氣不分。

引號使用 — 引用對話或特定稱謂符號不規範。

4. 結構
中心不明 — 文章缺乏核心主題。

段落銜接 — 段與段之間缺乏過渡與邏輯聯繫。

詳略失當 — 重點不夠突出，次要內容過於冗長。

開頭/結尾 — 起筆平淡或收結草率。

5. 內容
材料單薄 — 內容空洞，缺乏具體實例支撐。

脫離題意 — 離題或未能針對要求作答。

立意平淡 — 觀點缺乏深度或新意。

6. 表達
修辭貧乏 — 缺乏比喻、擬人等文學手法。

用詞單一 — 重複使用相同詞彙，語言不夠豐富。

語言乾澀 — 敘述生硬，缺乏感染力。

The aggregation rule, concretely:
For each (user, category) pair, maintain evidence_count and a recency-weighted severity score. Use an EWMA: severity_ewma = 0.3 * new_severity + 0.7 * old_severity on each new submission (only over submissions where the student's non-OCR-suspect errors are evaluated).
A category moves from watching → confirmed when both: evidence_count ≥ 3 AND the errors appear across ≥ 2 distinct submissions on ≥ 2 distinct days. This protects against one-bad-day bias.
A category moves to improving when the last 2 submissions show ≥50% reduction in that category's error rate. It moves to resolved when 3 consecutive submissions show zero errors in the category.
What's excluded from aggregation:

Every error with ocr_suspect = true
Errors the student flagged as "not my mistake" in feedback
Errors in submissions explicitly marked as drafts/practice

The UI should only ever surface confirmed weaknesses as "focus areas." Everything else is invisible to the student — this prevents the product from feeling like a constant criticism engine, and it means early submissions don't traumatize the student with a flood of red flags.

7. MVP Roadmap
Phase 0 — Foundations (2 weeks): auth, user model, rubric seed data for one grade level (pick the most valuable — likely 初三 for 中考 or 高三 for 高考 depending on your target), infra skeleton, CI/CD, one deployed environment.
Phase 1 — Writing MVP (6–8 weeks): typed-text submission, analysis pipeline, annotated feedback view, revision workspace, basic dashboard, feedback-capture widget. Ship this to 10–20 real students before building more.
Phase 2 — Handwriting (4–6 weeks): photo upload, OCR integration, verification UX, OCR-suspect propagation into error records. The analysis pipeline doesn't change — only the input method.
Phase 3 — Weakness Engine (3–4 weeks): aggregation service, weakness report UI, focus-area recommendations on the dashboard. Most of this can be built earlier at low fidelity, but polishing needs real submission volume, so sequence it here.
Phase 4 — Reading Analysis (4–6 weeks): passage + questions flow, answer rubric, analysis prompts tuned for comprehension vs. composition.
Phase 5 — Polish & Scale: parent/teacher views, assignment mode, notifications, mobile app wrapper, usage-based optimizations.
Do not skip getting Phase 1 in front of real students. Every architectural decision downstream improves dramatically once you've watched five students use the MVP.

8. Tech Stack Recommendation

Frontend: Next.js (App Router) + TypeScript + Tailwind + shadcn/ui. TanStack Query for server state. Zustand for local UI state.
Backend: Python 3.12 + FastAPI. Python wins here because your AI/ML tooling, Chinese NLP libraries (jieba, HanLP, pkuseg), and LLM SDKs all live there natively.
DB / Cache / Queue: Postgres 16, Redis 7, Celery (or ARQ if you prefer async-native).
Object storage: Cloudflare R2 (cheap egress) or Aliyun OSS if deploying in mainland China.
LLM: This depends on deployment region. For mainland China: Qwen-Max, DeepSeek, or Doubao — all handle Chinese rubrics excellently and satisfy data residency. For international: Claude or GPT-4-class models. Plan for multi-provider from day one (an abstraction layer of ~100 lines saves you later).
OCR: Baidu OCR's handwriting endpoint for mainland. Tencent as backup. Azure Document Intelligence if you need international.
Chinese NLP utilities: jieba for segmentation, HanLP for deeper parsing if needed, pypinyin for pinyin operations.
Deployment: Docker Compose on a single VPS for MVP. Move to managed Kubernetes (ACK / EKS) only when you have real scaling pressure. Don't over-engineer.
Observability: Sentry, PostHog, Grafana + Prometheus when you care about infra metrics.


9. Development Effort Estimate
Assuming a small team of 1 full-stack engineer + 1 AI/backend engineer + 1 part-time designer, with a Chinese-language teacher available for rubric review:

Phase 0: 2 weeks
Phase 1 (Writing MVP): 6–8 weeks
Phase 2 (Handwriting): 4–6 weeks
Phase 3 (Weakness Engine): 3–4 weeks
Phase 4 (Reading): 4–6 weeks
Phase 5 (Polish): ongoing

Total to a complete product: ~5–6 months. MVP (Phase 0+1) in the market: ~2–2.5 months.
Solo engineer: roughly double the Phase 1–4 durations. The design and rubric work is not parallelizable beyond a point.
The non-engineering work that people underestimate: curating rubrics, writing prompt guidelines per grade level, sourcing reading passages with licensing you can defend, and teacher review loops. Budget ~20–30% of total effort for this.

10. Risks and Mitigation
Handwritten Chinese OCR accuracy. Student handwriting varies wildly. Mitigation: the verification step is non-negotiable; set expectations that OCR is a draft; measure OCR accuracy per-student and adapt UI (tighter threshold for messier writers); never let OCR-suspect characters become weaknesses.
LLM inconsistency on Chinese grammar judgments. Models occasionally "correct" correct Chinese or miss real errors. Mitigation: rubric-anchored prompting; evidence-span requirement; teacher review sampling (~5% of submissions reviewed by a real teacher for calibration); the feedback_events loop to detect systematic errors and adjust prompts.
Product drifting toward a cheating tool. The pull is strong — students will ask for rewrites. Mitigation: the analysis layer never outputs a rewritten essay; revision is scaffolded with Socratic prompts; student must write the revision themselves; track "improvement delta" rather than "final score," which rewards learning over polish.
Discouragement from too much criticism. Early submissions will surface many errors. Mitigation: the watching vs confirmed distinction above; dashboard only shows 2–3 focus areas; always surface strengths; celebrate improvement explicitly; tutor-voice tone calibration enforced at the prompt level.
Data privacy and PIPL/GDPR compliance. You're handling minors' work. Mitigation: encrypt at rest; signed URLs with short TTLs for images; explicit parental consent flow if you target under-14 users; configurable retention (e.g., auto-delete images after 90 days, keep analyses longer); region-appropriate hosting.
LLM cost at scale. Analysis per submission can easily cost ¥0.5–¥2. At 1000 daily submissions that's material. Mitigation: multi-tier model routing (strong model for essays, smaller model for revision feedback and coaching text); cache rubric-prompt prefixes; batch non-urgent jobs; offer tiered plans.
Grade-level calibration drift. A 初一 rubric applied to a 高二 essay will give nonsense. Mitigation: require grade_level on every submission; rubric is loaded by grade+genre; auto-detect mismatches ("this essay seems above your declared level — want to switch?").
Teacher/parent trust. If they don't believe the analysis, the product dies. Mitigation: every error shows evidence; analyses are inspectable; sample-based teacher review; gradually introduce a teacher dashboard that lets them verify or override.